Although originally associated only with medical institutions, the prevalence of methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) in other areas is continually rising. Over the last few years, the bacteria have been detected as livestock-associated MRSA (LA-MRSA) in pigs, cattle, and poultry, as well as in animal keepers and veterinarians, who are considered an exposure risk group ([@CIT0001]). The main focus is on ST398, a clonal complex that is mutually transferable between livestock and humans ([@CIT0002]). This zoonotic potential underscores the importance of monitoring MRSA transmission at the human-animal interface. Studies have shown that individuals working closely with livestock are more likely to be colonized by LA-MRSA, raising concerns about its spread into the broader community ([@CIT0003]). Furthermore, LA-MRSA strains such as ST398 often exhibit resistance not only to beta-lactam antibiotics but also to other antimicrobial classes, complicating treatment options ([@CIT0004]). Consequently, the emergence of LA-MRSA has significant public health implications, highlighting the need for coordinated surveillance and infection control measures across both veterinary and human healthcare settings.

